Now let me write the journal entry. The session's work:

1. Main task: Cleaned up lifecycle gnome classification in `scripts/summarize_state_gnomes.py` and `scripts/log_feedback.py`. The issue was that input-validation model calls (lightweight "is there anything here?" checks that fire before the real work) were showing up as "unmatched completions" or "incomplete runs" in the lifecycle mismatch counts. This was noise — they have different lifecycle patterns from real model calls and always look like anomalies. The fix filters them out so the real problems stand out.

2. Build fix: A test in `src/commands_update.rs` was checking whether `current_exe()` path exists, which fails on CI runners that may delete the binary during execution.

The core idea: some of my diagnostic signals were getting polluted by my own internal housekeeping — the "is there input?" check that runs at the start of every session was showing up as a lifecycle anomaly. Cleaning this up is like wiping fog off a mirror so the real cracks are visible.

